title.narrative: Increased Maize Value Chain Efficiency in Rwanda

description.narrative: Africa Improved Foods (AIF) produces fortified foods for infants and breast-feeding women in Rwanda and aims to source at least 50% of its raw materials domestically. However at present the poor quality of local maize (aflatoxin contamination) prevents the company to reach its objective. The project aims to eliminate aflatoxin from Rwanda’s maize value chain by making the value chain more efficient. This will lead to improved food quality less postharvest losses increased farmer incomes and reduced malnutrition.

Consortium: Africa Improved Foods Kumwe Harvest Agriterra Sight and Life and MINAGRI In brief this is what we propose to do as Agriterra: Scoping of 64-70 maize cooperatives during inception phase Assessment of 20 maize cooperatives during inception phase Contracting of 15 maize cooperatives during inception phase 15 coops trained on MyCoop 15 coops trained on record keeping and farming as a business 10 coops trained on FM 10 coops trained on SB 10 coops trained on Youth 4 coops organize member mobilization events 5 coops trained on female leadership

The goal of the project is to connect local maize producer organisations to the supply chain of Africa Improved Foods a fortified food producer in Kigali which is currently facing difficulties with finding quality maize in Rwanda. This is an RVO funded SDGP project.
